<paragraph id="439A9882FDBE6451909FDB5736D6B23A" pageId="5" pageNumber="172">
The pure red populations of the Kendevan region have been described as ssp. kendevanica Tremewan, 1977, and populations with the same phenotype are found further south-west to Zanjan (Figs 49-54). Similar pure red populations occur in the Van 
<normalizedToken id="65A175B05A57E8EC9E61EAD1D60D1183" originalValue="Gölü">Goelue</normalizedToken>
region in eastern Turkey (ssp. placida Bang-Haas, 1913), while the Zagros range, the Iranian Talysh and Azerbaijan-e Sharqi are predominantly inhabited by populations with mixed characters of yellow forewings and red hindwings (Figs 43-45) or yellow fore- and hindwings (Figs 40-42, 46-48). A unique character that distinguishes all of these populations of 
<taxonomicName id="CADA56CBB6B208B9D66D7B51F3D0F82B" class="Insecta" family="Zygaenidae" genus="Zygaena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zygaena tamara" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tamara">Zygaena tamara</taxonomicName>
from all other 
<taxonomicName id="DA2E94A049F72C858CEBDE5EC35AB2E1" authority="Hübner, 1819" authorityName="Hübner" authorityYear="1819" class="Insecta" family="Zygaenidae" genus="Mesembrynus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesembrynus" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesembrynus</taxonomicName>
species is the red abdominal cingulum that is present on two to three segments in the females and on three segments in the males (Figs 40-54, 63), a character that is in strong contrast to the newly discovered populations from the northern side of the Alborz range, which we here describe as 
<taxonomicName id="A7573C5DF6B489EE13FC32018803649D" class="Insecta" family="Zygaenidae" genus="Zygaena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zygaena tamara subsp. dailamica" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="tamara" subSpecies="dailamica">Zygaena tamara dailamica</taxonomicName>
ssp. n.
</paragraph>
